    "nodes": [
      {
        "id": "n1",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 43.29032258064515,
          "y": 382.4434996482545
        },
        "width": 400,
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "import numpy as np\nfrom scipy.constants import c\n\n# ---- Fixed system parameters (PoC scale; B/Fs/Tp reduced for tractability) ----\nfc   = 9.65e9          # X-band carrier [Hz]\nB    = 300e6/4            # chirp bandwidth [Hz]   (real: 600e6)\nTp   = 10e-6           # pulse width [s]        (real: 30e-6)\nFs   = 360e6/4            # range sampling rate [Hz] \nPRF  = 4000.0          # pulse repetition frequency [Hz]\nH    = 514e3           # orbit altitude [m]\nV    = 7600.0          # platform velocity [m/s]\nlook = np.deg2rad(25)  # off-nadir angle [rad]\nLa   = 4.8             # antenna length, azimuth (along-track) [m]\nLr   = 0.8             # antenna length, range (elevation) [m]\n# Range swath half-width [m]. Sets the observed range window (Nr grid). Physical\n# upper bound is the elevation beam footprint theta_rg*R0 ~ +/-11 km (lam/Lr*R0);\n# real SAR narrows it via the receive window. 2 km here: wide enough for image\n# targets, far cheaper than the full 11 km. (Was hardcoded 80 m in n2 — too small.)\nR_half = 4000.0\nprint('params set: fc=%.2fGHz B=%.0fMHz Tp=%.0fus PRF=%.0f La=%.1fm Lr=%.1fm' % (fc/1e9, B/1e6, Tp*1e6, PRF, La, Lr))\n\n# ============================================================================\n# Scene controls (sar-visualizer parity). The focused-image display window is\n# a 0-centred symmetric box of half-extent float(view_scale) [m]; point\n# targets (and later clutter) live inside it. n_targets / view_scale are set\n# by GUI blocks; these fallbacks apply when those haven't run yet.\n# ============================================================================\n# n_targets and view_scale come from GUI blocks that run earlier in the\n# flow. view_scale comes from the GUI dropdown (Crop Area [m]) as a half-extent\n# metres value held as a string, so callers use float(view_scale). No fallbacks\n# here on purpose: if a downstream node sees NameError it\n# means the GUI block is missing or out of order — that must surface as a real\n# error, not be hidden by a default.\n\ndef make_rand(seed):\n    \"\"\"mulberry32 PRNG (exact port). float in [0,1).\"\"\"\n    box = {'a': int(seed) & 0xFFFFFFFF}\n    M = 0xFFFFFFFF\n    def _rand():\n        box['a'] = (box['a'] + 0x6d2b79f5) & M\n        t = box['a']\n        t = (((t ^ (t >> 15)) & M) * ((1 | t) & M)) & M           # Math.imul(t^(t>>>15), 1|t)\n        t = ((t + ((((t ^ (t >> 7)) & M) * ((61 | t) & M)) & M)) & M) ^ t  # +Math.imul(t^(t>>>7),61|t), ^t\n        t &= M\n        return ((t ^ (t >> 14)) & M) / 4294967296.0\n    return _rand\n\ndef make_point_targets(count, half_az_m, half_range_m, seed, R0):\n    \"\"\"Point targets, sar-visualizer parity. T1 is always the centre\n    reference (az 0, slant R0); extras are seeded-random inside +/-0.85*half\n    so they sit clearly within the display window.\"\"\"\n    out = [('T1', 0.0, R0)]\n    rnd = make_rand(seed)\n    az_span = half_az_m * 0.85\n    r_span = half_range_m * 0.85\n    for i in range(1, int(count)):\n        az_m = (rnd() * 2 - 1) * az_span\n        sr_m = R0 + (rnd() * 2 - 1) * r_span\n        out.append(('T%d' % (i + 1), az_m, sr_m))\n    return out\n# Plot helpers (surface3d_gl, surface3d_pair_gl, upsample_complex, upsample_complex_range, ...) are\n# defined in the \"Plot Library\" node (unconnected, runs first) and shared via\n# the kernel namespace. They are workspace-local, NOT HiyoCanvas core. See that\n# node's SPEC and CLAUDE.md (\"common helpers go in a visible Library node\").",
            "label": "Common Parameters",
            "spec": "Shared SAR system parameters (TerraSAR-X reference, X-band).\nBound once here and read by every downstream block via the shared kernel namespace.\n\nReal values (full-res spec):\n- fc 9.65 GHz, B 600 MHz, Tp 30 us, Fs 720 MHz (1.2*B), PRF 4 kHz\n- H 514 km, V 7600 m/s, look 25 deg, La 4.8 m\n\nSimulation note: this PoC lowers B/Fs 10x and Tp 3x so the grid stays browser-tractable; geometry params unchanged."
          },
          "codeCollapsed": true
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "n2",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 517.2533573264079,
          "y": -11.33625912520529
        },
        "width": 400,
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "# ---- Derived quantities ----\nlam     = c / fc                 # wavelength [m]\nKr      = B / Tp                 # chirp rate [Hz/s]\nR0      = H / np.cos(look)       # T1 slant range [m]\ntheta_a = lam / La               # first-null beamwidth [rad]\naz_foot = theta_a * R0           # azimuth footprint [m]\n\n# ---- Range grid ----\nt_r_center = 2 * R0 / c\ndt_r = 1 / Fs\n# Receive window half-width in TIME. Two-way propagation: a target at\n# slant-range offset R_half returns at round-trip delay 2*R_half/c, so the\n# window half-width is 2*R_half/c. (Was R_half/c — one-way — which made the\n# range axis reach only R_half/2 + extras, e.g. R_half=3000 -> +/-2549 m.)\n# A small 5% guard band keeps targets at +/-R_half clear of the NUFFT fold\n# edge. Range axis spans +/- 1.05*R_half (proportional, e.g. 3000 -> 3150).\nRANGE_GUARD = 1.05\nt_r_half_window = 2 * R_half / c * RANGE_GUARD\nNr = int(np.ceil(2 * t_r_half_window / dt_r));  Nr += Nr % 2\nt_r = t_r_center + (np.arange(Nr) - Nr // 2) * dt_r\n\n# ---- Azimuth grid ----\naz_extent = 300.0 + az_foot / 2 + 200.0\nNa = int(np.ceil(2 * az_extent / V * PRF));  Na += Na % 2\neta = (np.arange(Na) - Na // 2) / PRF\naz_pos = V * eta\n\n# ---- Transmit reference chirp (baseband), centered at t=0 ----\nt_ref = (np.arange(Nr) - Nr // 2) * dt_r\nref_chirp = ((np.abs(t_ref) <= Tp/2).astype(np.float32)\n             * np.exp(1j * np.pi * Kr * t_ref**2)).astype(np.complex64)\nprint('Kr=%.3e Hz/s  R0=%.1f km  grid Nr=%d Na=%d' % (Kr, R0/1e3, Nr, Na))",
            "label": "Generate chirp signal",
            "spec": "Generate the transmit linear-FM (chirp) pulse and the imaging grid.\n\nParameters (from mindmap):\n- Frequency: min/max  -> chirp sweeps fc-B/2 .. fc+B/2\n- Pulse width: Tp\n- PRF: pulse repetition frequency\n\nPhysics:\n- chirp rate  Kr = B/Tp\n- baseband chirp  s(t) = rect(|t|<=Tp/2) * exp(j*pi*Kr*t^2)\n- wavelength lam = c/fc, ref slant range R0 = H/cos(look)\n\nThis block also designs the range/azimuth sampling grid (Nr,Na,t_r,eta,az_pos) the echo will live on."
          },
          "codeCollapsed": true
        }
      },
